> A common alternative to the ATmega328 is the "picoPower" ATmega328P.

CPU type	8-bit AVR
Maximum CPU speed	20 MHz
Performance	20 MIPS at 20 MHz
Flash memory	32 KB
    Program memory
    Boot loader lives at the bottom
    Unlimited writes, but can only write entire pages at a time
    See "AVR109: Self Programming": https://ww1.microchip.com/downloads/en/AppNotes/doc1644.pdf
SRAM	2 KB
    Data memory
EEPROM	1 KB
    Unlike flash, can write individual bytes, but has limited writes over its lifetime
    Max 100,000 writes, says https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AVR_microcontrollers
    Could be used for e.g. persistent configuration, says http://rjhcoding.com/avr-asm-memory-types.php
    So, basically like the "hard drive"
